    "body": "**Describe the bug**\r\n\r\nCython 0.29.23 does not work correctly with pypy >= 3.7.4 if there is an `exec()` command in the pyx file and if C++ compiler is used. To the best of my understanding, this is related to a cast that was needed as a workaround for pypy<3.7.4 but is [not needed anymore](https://foss.heptapod.net/pypy/pypy/-/commit/d5c6dc6817c4d44fe392aebb322087bb350ab2d4) in pypy>=3.7.4. This workaround has been already removed in cython master branch [here](https://github.com/cython/cython/commit/1027db04fb7c5bbfea2b9bcdfce0b1f384e26a93#diff-11f7af60992f9e640ea52fb75d02b03c1521f07685948e95b46df97e743d82f2). I would suggest to backport this fix also to cython 0.29.x.\r\n\r\n**To Reproduce**\r\nCode to reproduce the behaviour:\r\n```bash\r\necho 'exec(\"a=2; print(a)\")' > demo.pyx\r\ncat > setup.py << EOF\r\nfrom distutils.core import setup, Extension\r\nfrom Cython.Build import cythonize\r\n\r\nsetup (name = 'PackageName',\r\n       version = '1.0',\r\n       description = 'This is a demo package',\r\n       ext_modules=cythonize(Extension(name=\"demo\",sources=[\"demo.pyx\"],language=\"c++\"),language_level=3)\r\n       )\r\nEOF\r\npypy setup.py build\r\n```\r\n\r\n**Expected behavior**\r\nWith pypy 3.7.4 I see the following error:\r\n```\r\ndemo.cpp:1568:18: error: no matching function for call to 'PyPyEval_EvalCode'\r\n        result = PyEval_EvalCode((PyCodeObject *)o, globals, locals);\r\n                 ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\r\n/Users/bussi/.conda/envs/pypy37/include/pypy_decl.h:266:25: note: expanded from macro 'PyEval_EvalCode'\r\n#define PyEval_EvalCode PyPyEval_EvalCode\r\n                        ^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\r\n/Users/bussi/.conda/envs/pypy37/include/pypy_decl.h:267:30: note: candidate function not viable: no known conversion from 'PyCodeObject *' to 'struct _object *' for 1st\r\n      argument\r\nPyAPI_FUNC(struct _object *) PyEval_EvalCode(struct _object *arg0, struct _object *arg1, struct _object *arg2);\r\n                             ^\r\n/Users/bussi/.conda/envs/pypy37/include/pypy_decl.h:266:25: note: expanded from macro 'PyEval_EvalCode'\r\n#define PyEval_EvalCode PyPyEval_EvalCode\r\n```\r\n\r\nWith pypy 3.7.3 the extension can be compiled correctly. Notice that if I build a C extension (rather than a C++ one) a warning is issued but compilation succeeds. So this is visible only with the following combination:\r\n- cython < 3\r\n- C++ extension\r\n- pypy >= 3.7.4\r\n- an `exec()` instruction in the pyx file\r\n\r\n**Environment (please complete the following information):**\r\n\r\nI reproduced it on my MacOS, cython 0.29.23 and pypy 3.7.3 (working) or 3.7.4 (not working). However, the same happened in a more complicated context within a range of operating systems using the same version of Pypy, as it can be seen in the logs of this [pull request on conda-forge](https://github.com/conda-forge/py-plumed-feedstock/pull/17).",
